    <text>
        <body>
            <p>
                <anchor xml:id="Hlk196896749"/>Introduction
            </p>
            <p>Archaeological data are typically collected over long periods by various individuals at different times and locations, often including legacy data throughout the curation process. Archaeological data are also known to have inherent vagueness, such as inaccuracies in dating systems or in categorical variables, such as the interpretation of the functions attributed to a site or phase, as we may not always have enough information to assign a precise value (Taheri et al. 2019). Furthermore, the uncertainty in data is often influenced by the person providing the value ("archaeological annotator").</p>
            <p>For some years now, research in mathematics, computational sciences, and archaeological theory has addressed the uncertainty in archaeological data and its links to annotator expertise/confidence (Kae et al. 2023; Fusco 2016; Runz, 2008; Martin- Rodilla / González-Pérez 2019; Tobalina-Pulido / González-Pérez 2020; Martín- Rodilla / Tobalina Pulido 2024). This study uses real data and three annotators with varying expertise to evaluate concordance metrics for fuzzy annotations, applying computational linguistics and vector distance methods within fuzzy data models.</p>
            <p>Inter-annotator agreement metrics</p>
            <p>In computational linguistics and engineering, inter-annotator agreement metrics ensure the reliability of annotations in tasks like text labeling or image classification. Common measures include Cohen's Kappa, which accounts for chance agreement (-1 to 1, with 1 being perfect), and Fleiss's Kappa, suited for multiple annotators (also ranging from -1 to 1). Krippendorff's Alpha is highly adaptable, accommodating various data types, with values from 1 (unanimous agreement) to negative (systematic disagreement). For fuzzy data ([0,1] interval), these metrics often require data discretization1.</p>
            <p>Vector distance-based approaches</p>
            <p>Vector distance metrics offer a mathematical approach to measure the disagreement between annotators by analysing the membership vectors they produce. The main metrics used include:</p>
