            <p>Table 1. Summary of Distance and Correlation Metrics</p>
            <p>All the described metrics require pairwise comparisons of annotators. While more advanced mathematical approaches exist to address annotator disagreement, their complexity and steep learning curve make them less practical for use by archaeologists and cultural heritage professionals. Therefore, we focus on well-known and straightforward vector distance metrics.</p>
            <p>Case Study</p>
            <p>Archaeological fuzzy data case study</p>
            <p>The Santa María de Hito site, located in Valderredible (Cantabria, Spain), has provided valuable chronological data through both ceramic materials and absolute radiocarbon dating. The Roman levels date the villa's use to the 3rd-4th centuries. Several radiocarbon dates from the necropolis offer high chronological precision2. While the necropolis' function is easier to define with fewer uncertainties, the exact use of the villa remains less clear, though it is well-defined in the literature. The data has been extracted from the article "Dataciones absolutas para la Arqueología de época histórica en Cantabria" (Gutiérrez Cuenca 2002). This site is suitable for uncertainty analysis because of its chronological and functional aspects. The ambiguity surrounding the villa's function— whether residential, agricultural, or both—enables the evaluation of how annotators with varying expertise levels influence data interpretation and the assigned uncertainty. Three annotators with varying levels of expertise in both the periods and the site's usage were selected to assess the variations in annotation. Three annotators with varying expertise in the site's periods and usage were selected to assess annotation variations. They were provided with a template to include their annotations, which included the following fields: annotator's initials, categories of use (e.g., villa, religious, habitat), certainty about the assigned use, expertise in each use, periods assigned to the site, certainty of chronological</p>
            <p>2 With the following results: CSIC-838 (1430±40), CSIC-840 (1360±40), CSIC-837 (1320±50), and CSIC-</p>
            <p>839 (980±40), according to E. Gutiérrez Cuenca (2002).</p>
            <p>attribution, and expertise in each period. The variables were rated on a scale from 0 to 1, with decimal values allowed. The annotators and their characteristics are as follows:</p>
