            <p>
                <hi style="font-size:10.5pt">In both Euclidean and Manhattan distances, higher values reflect greater discrepancies, with annotators 1 and 3 showing closer agreement than with annotator 2. Cosine distance, which measures vector orientation similarity, also identifies annotators 1 and 3 as the most aligned. Chebyshev distance reinforces this, showing the least disagreement (0.9) between annotators 1 and 3, compared to others (1.0). Correlation analysis, such as Pearson’s, highlights a strong positive correlation for annotators 1 and 3 (0.961) and weaker or negative correlations for others (-0.457 for 2 vs. 3). Together, these metrics reveal higher concordance between annotators 1 and 3, with annotator 2 being less aligned.</hi>
            </p>
            <p>Conclusions</p>
            <p>The results highlight a low level of agreement between the annotators (with corresponds to the current works on the importance of this dimension on the study of vagueness in archaeological data). However, there is some moderate agreement between annotator 1 and 3, which could be explored further. Current data show disagreement in use and chronology but do not consider annotator expertise. Future work will incorporate expertise adjustments through direct smoothing (Pavlov / Nott, 2016) and proportional smoothing (Li / Chen, 2006), refining annotations by adjusting for expertise. These methods aim to reduce uncertainty and better integrate annotator expertise into the analysis. Its ability to measure interpretations is key to standardizing methods, improving collaboration, and enhancing objectivity in a field that often reinterprets legacy data</p>
